{"parentUuid":"4a15ef6d-d748-4d9c-a9f4-3d2beba0398d","isSidechain":false,"message":{"id":"345dca8b-592e-4708-bd59-2c5d0a0f68ab","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"deepseek-reasoner","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking why AppData can't be moved and if there's a way to do it.\n\nAppData contains application-specific data, settings, caches, and configurations. It's divided into three subfolders:\n- **Local**: Machine-specific data, caches - cannot be moved/roamed\n- **Roaming**: Settings that sync across machines - can potentially be relocated via symbolic links\n- **LocalLow**: Low-integrity data similar to Local\n\nThe answer is: AppData CAN be moved, but not by simple cut-paste. There are a few approaches:\n\n1. **Symbolic links (mklink)**: Move the folder to D: drive and create a symbolic link back to the original path. This works for most applications but some don't handle it well.\n\n2. **Windows Junction Points**: Similar to symlinks but for directories.\n\n3. **Use Windows built-in \"Location\" tab** - Some versions support this for AppData.\n\n4. **Specific app settings**: Many apps allow you to change their data paths internally (e.g., WeChat, QQ, browsers).\n\n5. **Third-party tools**: Tools like \"AppData Move\" or symbolic link makers.\n\nHowever, there are significant risks:\n- Some applications hardcode paths and will break\n- After Windows updates, the symlinks might not be followed correctly\n- Some apps recreate their AppData at the original location, causing dual storage\n- Performance impact if moving to HDD vs SSD\n- If the D: drive is removed or fails, apps may break catastrophically\n\nThe safest approach is to move only specific AppData folders that are known to be safe, like:\n- Browser caches (can redirect in browser settings)\n- WeChat/QQ file storage (can change in app settings)\n- Temp folders (already cleaned)\n- Specific app cache folders that apps can recreate\n\nA better question might be: what specific AppData folders are taking the most space, and can we address those individually?\n\nEarlier we saw:\n- Local: 29.02 GB\n- Roaming: 20.17 GB\n- LocalLow: 0.16 GB\n\nThe large items in Local were:\n- JianyingPro (剪映) cache - large yuv files, cache, dlls\n- Various updater caches (already cleaned)\n- Chrome cache\n- Temp files (already cleaned)\n\nFor Roaming:\n- Tencent (微信/QQ/Wetype) files\n- DingTalk\n- SogouExplorer\n- Various app data\n\nLet me provide a practical answer - yes AppData can be moved through symlinks, but it's risky for some apps. A better approach is to move specific large AppData items that are safe.","signature":"345dca8b-592e-4708-bd59-2c5d0a0f68ab"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5590,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":54528,"output_tokens":1045,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"type":"assistant","uuid":"6712a31a-15d9-4d71-912d-0155a01a8d15","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:27.597Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Administrator","sessionId":"c7e06c6a-8029-4d8b-86ad-964b61b73a7b","version":"2.1.118","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
